{
  "text": "Extensive variability exists between hearing sensitivity of fish species, but in general, they are sensitive to low frequencies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , which puts them at risk from dredging noise. Some level of TTS has been reported in freshwater and marine fish exposed to low-frequency white noise (e.g. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Smith et al., 2004a, b) and vessel noise (e.g. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] in laboratory experiments. Results suggest that those with more specialized hearing experience a greater level of hearing loss. It should be noted, however, that these experiments did not focus on dredging noise, so noise characteristics and exposure durations likely vary from those experienced during dredging activities, which may alter the chance and extent of TTS.",
  "correct_citation": {
